dra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":16,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705183,"age":36,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705184,"age":46,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes Demoiselle de Montsorrel was born about 1050, in Normandy, France as the daughter of Hugh de Montsorrel. She had at least 5 sons with Philippe Maunsell. She died in Leicestershire, England, and was buried in Cromhall, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1050–":"umbes 1050–Surnud","1050–Female":"1050–Surnud","1040–Male":"1040–Surnud","1068–1100":"1068–1100","1070–Male":"1070–Surnud","1072–Male":"1072–Surnud","1073–Male":"1073–Surnud","1075–Male":"1075–Surnud","1017–Male":"1017–Surnud","about 1050":"umbes 1050","about 1072":"umbes 1072","about 1073":"umbes 1073","about 1070":"umbes 1070","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1075":"1075","1096":"1096","1073":"1073","1040":"1040","1072":"1072","1050":"1050","1070":"1070","1017":"1017","1068":"1068","1100":"1100","4 April 1068":"4. aprill 1068","about 1075":"umbes 1075","Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, England","Cromhall, Gloucestershire, England":"Cromhall, Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"about 1050–":"noin 1050–Kuollut","1050–Female":"1050–Kuollut","1040–Male":"1040–Kuollut","1068–1100":"1068–1100","1070–Male":"1070–Kuollut","1072–Male":"1072–Kuollut","1073–Male":"1073–Kuollut","1